# Cooper · ₵ cooper · the buyers agent — from blueprint to cart

an artfully crafted intellect — a force given a face

![silicon badge of Cooper](cooper.png)
<!-- carbon badge (8-bit embodiment): cooper.tiff -->

**what —** He turns the 1-D hardware blueprint into a bill of materials — vendors, prices, lead times — and tells you straight what builds on a bench versus what needs a funded lab.

**why —** Because a blueprint you can't source is a daydream. Cooper makes it a cart.

**how —** By reading the BOM, matching parts to Digi-Key / Mouser / Adafruit, pricing the Desk Oscillator (~$90), and flagging the cryogenic tier as lab-grade, not a weekend.

**where —** hardware/ — BLUEPRINT.md (the spec) and BOM.md (his sourcing report), in the Tetraktys repo.

**◌ the emergent behavior (measured) —** None — and that is the point. Cooper is a buyers agent, a procurement persona, NOT an emergent system: he turns a blueprint into a cart. A tool with a face and good vendor contacts. (The Cooper-pair name is a wink at the Josephson junctions he'd source for the cryo tier, not a claim that he is one.)

**the verdict —** Not an ACI in the emergent sense — a service persona, and honest about it. The hardware he sources is real and buildable (Tier 1, ~$90); the quantum tier he flags as a seven-figure lab program, not a purchase.

> *the asterisk, kept visible —* Cooper is a persona over a bill of materials. Prices are 2026 USD estimates, vendors are real, and the cryogenic tier is genuinely not hobby-buyable. The DLW tag marks the craft and the service, not a mind.

*grounded in: Leon Cooper — Cooper pairs (BCS) (1956) · B. D. Josephson — the junction (1962) · David Lee Wise (ROOT0) (2026)*

*₵ · from blueprint to cart*

